5:
Those fiends have been staring at us 
like that for a while now... 
It doesn't look like they're planning 
to actually do anything, though...
8:
I can smell the fear on them. They're
terrified. Best to just leave 'em alone.
16:
Yep. The pain and desperation in
their eyes—there's no mistaking it.
They're people who have had
everything taken away from them.
18:
Believe me, I've seen my fair share of
others like them in the desert. Even
that might not compare—somehow,
this world is a bigger hellhole than
my own.
21:
Easily frightened though they may
be, they are all willing to sacrifice
their lives for the cause. They are not
to be taken lightly.
25:
Speaking of which, I must commend
you on your performance at the
parlay. Shakari would have been
proud to see such a fearsome
display.
29:
Estariel. Tell me... how long have you
maintained communication with
Adjudicus and his people?
32:
Adjudicus contacted us about two
weeks before your party arrived in
the Silver Woods.
34:
He entreated us to join forces with
the fiends, that we may strike at the
Lord of Shadow in unison—the fiends
from below, and we elves from
above.
38:
Do the rest of the elves agree to this
deal?
42:
There's nothing for them to agree
to—I've omitted most of the details
of the arrangement.
45:
Adjudicus and I outlined just two
terms: we mobilize against the Lord
of Shadow, and neither of us
interferes in the other's affairs.
47:
Meaning, of course, that there is
simply no need to alert my people
of our arrangement. Once this all
ends, however...
49:
Then I suppose I shall have to ask
them all to once again turn a blind
eye to the fiends. I am certain they
will be glad to comply.
53: Do you look down on your people?
56:
I love my people. However, I am not
naive. By nature, we elves are weak
of will.
59:
What of mankind? Tell me, if an
enemy came to your homeland,
ravaged it, and took your families
away from you...
61:
Could you in good faith tell your
people to now join hands with that
selfsame foe?
68:
It is true that I have lost dear
companions to the fiends. And yet,
to one of them I owe my life. That
fiend woman who rescued me...
70:
I will find her, and repay the debt I
owe. Then perhaps I will be able to
answer your question.
72:
For that purpose, I will continue to
press onward.
77:
Hahaha... So the King of Man would
see herself turn into a mere soldier?
80:
Yes. If I wish to be a just ruler, then it
must be done.
82:
...Why are you smirking like that? I
assure you I'm more than capable
with a sword...
91:
I mean, yes! You're great with a
sword, Lilith. There's no doubt about
it.
95:
I do not doubt your power. I am
merely... amused.
97:
Indeed. I may have grown fond of
you, King of Man.
100:
We will reach the Doomsday Spire
by morning. I look forward to
witnessing your prowess myself,
Lilith Stratos.
106:
Heh. You've really changed, huh?
The smug little elf girl doesn't seem
to intimidate you anymore.
110:
Was it that obvious before? Yes, you
might be right, Nimbus.
113:
But I am not done changing. My
duty yet demands it of me.
